   "source": [
    "# Probability for Machine Learning: Quantifying Uncertainty\n",
    "\n",
    "Machine learning models are never 100% certain. Probability is the mathematical language we use to quantify that uncertainty.\n",
    "\n",
    "A classification model doesn't just say 'This is a cat'; it says `P(class=cat | image) = 0.95`. This means 'Given the image, I am 95% confident this is a cat.'\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook covers the core concepts of probability that are essential for understanding and building ML models."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "e33dce20",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from scipy.stats import norm, bernoulli, entropy\n",
    "\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "np.set_printoptions(precision=4, suppress=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d80cd340",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# 1. Probability Distributions: Describing Data\n",
    "\n",
    "A probability distribution describes the likelihood of all possible outcomes. We often try to 'fit' a known distribution to our data to model its underlying properties."
   ]
  },
    {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fit-to-data",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Example: Fitting a Normal Distribution\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's say we have data on people's heights. We can visualize this data with a histogram and then overlay a Normal (Gaussian) distribution to see how well it models the data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "69f23e62",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Generate some sample height data (in cm)\n",
    "heights = np.random.normal(170, 10, 1000)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the histogram of the data\n",
    "plt.hist(heights, bins=30, density=True, alpha=0.6, label='Height Data')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fit a normal distribution to the data\n",
    "mu, std = norm.fit(heights)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the PDF (Probability Density Function)\n",
    "xmin, xmax = plt.xlim()\n",
    "x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 100)\n",
    "p = norm.pdf(x, mu, std)\n",
    "plt.plot(x, p, 'k', linewidth=2, label='Fitted Normal Dist.')\n",
    "\n",
    "title = f\"Fit results: mu = {mu:.2f},  std = {std:.2f}\"\n",
    "plt.title(title)\n",